HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1492
By Vital
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Melvin Duley Cooper,
Jr., of Chattanooga.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Melvin Duley Cooper, Jr., of Chattanooga; and
WHEREAS, Mel Cooper was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, born on August 12, 1940, in Memphis, Melvin Duley Cooper, Jr., was the
eldest child of Melvin Duley Cooper, Sr., and Sidney Mae Wilson, and he grew up helping his
father in the family restaurant, the Electric Waffle Shop, that his grandmother started during the
Great Depression; and
WHEREAS, Mel Cooper graduated from Central High School in Memphis in 1958 and
Columbia University in New York in 1962; he returned to Memphis and taught in Shelby County
public schools before changing his career path after the premature deaths of both of his
parents; and
WHEREAS, under the mentorship of Bob Sharpe, an advocate of school development
work through Robert F. Sharpe and Company, Mel Cooper became the first development officer
for Memphis University School; and
WHEREAS, a trailblazer in the field of school fundraising, Mr. Cooper found a place in
the National Association of Independent Schools and the Council for Advancement and Support
of Education (CASE) and soon became a speaker, planner, and leader of workshops and
conferences; and
WHEREAS, in 1974, Mel Cooper relocated to Chattanooga to become the first
development officer for the McCallie School, where he built the school's development program
HJR1492
018220
- 1 -

from the ground up, retiring in 2007 after thirty-four years of managing ongoing-strategic plans
and cultivating major gifts with the board of trustees, leaving a substantial endowment and a
large staff of professionals; and
WHEREAS, a highly respected leader in his community, Mr. Cooper was known for
lending his time and talents to a number of schools and nonprofit organizations, including St.
Andrews-Sewanee School, Bright School, the Mental Health Association, Chattanooga Opera
Theater, Episcopal Commission of Southeast Tennessee, WTCI public television, A.I.M. Center,
Chattanooga Symphony and Opera, and Grace Episcopal Church; and
WHEREAS, after his retirement, he served on the Friends of Moccasin Bend, which
became National Park Partners; the Ed Johnson Committee, which established a memorial on
the Walnut Street Bridge; and the Houston Museum for Decorative Arts, which will open a fully
restored museum later this year; and
WHEREAS, among Mr. Cooper's many successful campaigns, the Sports and Athletic
Center and the Alumni Dining Hall stand as glowing examples of his transformative
achievements as a result of his dedication and drive; and
WHEREAS, no stranger to honors and accolades, Mel Cooper received the Robert Bell
Crow Memorial Award, the highest national award in independent school professional
advancement, from CASE in 2000 and the Burrows Award in 2002 for his service to St. Nicholas
School in Chattanooga; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Cooper was also deeply devoted to his family, and he always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, Mel Cooper enjoyed the loving companionship of his wife of forty-four years,
Eleanor McCallie Cooper, and was the proud father of Mae Cooper and Katie Cooper and the
devoted grandfather of Alp and Leotie; and
WHEREAS, Melvin Duley Cooper, Jr., leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and
probity in public life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his
chosen endeavors; and
- 2 - 018220

WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Melvin Duley Cooper, Jr., reflecting fondly upon
his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage
and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Cooper.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
